---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Censorship Detector (India) | Aryan">
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-container px-6">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.35em] text-white/50">Project</p>
        <h1 class="mt-4 font-heading text-4xl">Censorship Detector (India)</h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-white/60">Mapping Digital Borders Through Network Measurements</p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-4">
          <a
            href="https://indiancensorshipproject.streamlit.app/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            class="rounded-xl bg-white/10 px-6 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-white transition hover:bg-white/20"
          >
            Live demo
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://github.com/Aryanb1102/Indian-Censorship-Project"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            class="rounded-xl border border-white/20 px-6 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-white/80 transition hover:text-white"
          >
            GitHub repo
          </a>
        </div>
        <div class="article-content mt-10">
          <h2>Censorship Detector (India): Mapping Digital Borders Through Network Measurements</h2>
          <p>
            Censorship Detector is a small, reproducible measurement project that treats internet access as an
            infrastructure problem rather than a content problem. Instead of asking what people are saying online, it
            asks a more basic question: what can users in India actually reach, from where, and through which technical
            bottlenecks? The project is designed as a lightweight “digital border probe” for India’s internet—capturing
            how state regulation, ISP enforcement, and platform-level restrictions show up at the level of DNS
            resolution, TCP connectivity, HTTP(S) responses, and TLS certificate trust.
          </p>
          <p>
            I built a curated corpus of ~100 India-relevant domains across four categories: News &amp; Politics, Social &amp;
            Streaming, Government &amp; Public Services, and Civil Society &amp; NGOs. For each domain, the detector runs
            layered tests (DNS → TCP → HTTP(S) → TLS), logs normalized outcomes (success, timeout, access denied,
            connection errors), and extracts certificate issuer metadata to map trust infrastructure. To avoid
            overfitting to a single network snapshot, I also ingest and filter OONI Web Connectivity measurements for
            India and compute per-domain failure rates as an external, longitudinal signal. Where possible, I compare
            measurements across vantages (India home ISP vs. a foreign VPN exit) to surface geoblocking candidates and
            distinguish “globally broken” sites from location-specific interference.
          </p>
          <p>
            The output is a structured dataset (raw_measurements.csv + domain-level summaries) plus an analysis layer
            that generates plots such as HTTP outcomes by category, OONI failure-rate distributions, and TLS issuer
            breakdowns. On top of this, I implement a transparent heuristic classifier that groups domains into
            interpretable buckets like normal, policy_blocked (e.g., adult/piracy enforcement), app_ban_partial (e.g.,
            remnants of app bans), and infra_flaky (common among state portals). The result is not a definitive
            censorship oracle, but a practical measurement tool that makes invisible infrastructure constraints
            legible—and creates a foundation for connecting technical evidence to policy questions around Section 69A
            blocking, platform compliance, and the “splinternet” debate.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Live demo: https://indiancensorshipproject.streamlit.app/</li>
            <li>Repository: https://github.com/Aryanb1102/Indian-Censorship-Project</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Tech stack: Python, pandas, requests/ssl, DNS tooling, Streamlit</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
